WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:27.000
So, I think many of us have experienced this where we've created a cool shiny application

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.559
and you want to share it with somebody.

00:00:29.559 --> 00:00:36.799
So here's an example, this is from our shiny gallery, somebody who created a data visualization

00:00:36.799 --> 00:00:42.360
application for data from the Center for Disease Control.

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:46.560
And let's say you've created a cool app like this and you want to share it with somebody.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:52.599
Well, doing that right now is very easy, that's always been one of the really easy things

00:00:52.599 --> 00:00:53.599
to do with shiny.

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:58.200
You just send somebody a URL, they go to it and they can see your app.

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:08.360
But if you wanted to share not just the app, but the work that you've done in the app,

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:18.120
like let's say I've interacted with this application and I've selected a particular disease, date

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:23.760
range, location, and so on, and I want to share that with somebody, the particular state

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:27.760
of this application, that isn't as easy to do.

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:37.120
So you might find yourself writing emails like this, and I'll just read this out loud.

00:01:37.120 --> 00:01:42.160
So this is to the boss, subject pertussis data, hi boss, here's the app that shows the

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:43.160
latest data.

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:49.839
To see the results, go to this URL, for disease name, select pertussis, for choose date range,

00:01:49.839 --> 00:01:56.000
make it start from 2014, for plot type, choose weekly data by year, for plot options, check

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.599
the date, include alert thresholds, and then you should see what I'm seeing, enjoy your

00:02:01.599 --> 00:02:02.599
holidays.

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:06.519
So you may have, if you've written shiny applications to share with people, you may have done this

00:02:06.519 --> 00:02:16.080
before, and, sorry, this control panel keeps popping up, so you may have done this before,

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:25.559
but it would be nice if you could write an email that's more like this, here's the latest

00:02:25.559 --> 00:02:30.240
data, just send a URL, enjoy your holidays.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:35.160
And that particular application, the example that I showed is just, there's only four settings

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:38.679
on there, but there's still, you have to say, do this, and this, and this, and this.

00:02:38.679 --> 00:02:44.240
And for more complex apps, you might have an even longer set of instructions for how

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:47.600
to get to a particular state.

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:54.399
So in order to do that, to send somebody not just an app, but also the state of the

00:02:54.399 --> 00:03:02.240
application, we've introduced this feature called bookmarkable state, and this was released

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:09.919
with shiny 0.14, which came out in September, I believe.

00:03:09.919 --> 00:03:13.639
So now I'm going to illustrate this with a very simple example, I'm going to illustrate

00:03:13.639 --> 00:03:16.119
how you use it.

00:03:16.119 --> 00:03:22.520
So I'm going to start with a very simple demo app that should be easy to follow.

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:31.539
So this is an application with just one input and one output, and I'll show you it running

00:03:31.539 --> 00:03:32.539
live here.

00:03:32.539 --> 00:03:40.320
Okay, so we'll run that, and I enter text, hello world, and it outputs the same text

00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:41.320
down here.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:44.279
So that's the basic app.

00:03:44.279 --> 00:03:49.720
Now if I want to be able to bookmark the state of this app, there's just a few changes

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:53.279
that I have to make to the code.

00:03:53.279 --> 00:04:01.839
So this is what it looks like, and this is with a, this is for a single file app, just

00:04:01.839 --> 00:04:04.639
an app.r.

00:04:04.639 --> 00:04:08.199
So here's the few changes that I need to make.

00:04:08.199 --> 00:04:18.160
First off, the user interface, the UI part of it needs to be a function that returns

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:19.440
the UI components.

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:24.160
So instead of UI being fluid page, it's a function that returns this fluid page, etc.,

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:25.160
etc.

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:29.160
It takes one argument called request, which, that argument doesn't actually get used, but

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:30.720
the function needs to take that.

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:35.200
It doesn't get used in this case, but there's other reasons to use it that aren't related

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:36.200
to bookmarking.

00:04:37.119 --> 00:04:42.679
The next thing that we need to add is a bookmark button somewhere so that the user has a way

00:04:42.679 --> 00:04:47.119
to actually tell us that they want to bookmark a particular state.

00:04:47.119 --> 00:04:53.119
And then when you call shiny app, you just need to add this part at the end, enable bookmarking

00:04:53.119 --> 00:04:54.119
equals URL.

00:04:54.119 --> 00:04:59.799
You just need to add that one argument.

00:04:59.799 --> 00:05:03.040
And so this is the single file app, the app.r version.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:11.079
If you want to do a, if you're writing an app with UI.r and server.r, it's very similar.

00:05:11.079 --> 00:05:20.640
You say UI is a function, add a bookmark button, and then you have, in your global.r, you say

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:22.160
enable bookmarking URL.

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:26.959
This time it's a function called enable bookmarking instead of an argument to a function.

00:05:26.959 --> 00:05:28.440
So that's all you need to do.

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:31.920
And I'll show you how that works, what that looks like.

00:05:32.799 --> 00:05:34.399
I'll run my code here.

00:05:34.399 --> 00:05:39.399
All right, so hello world.

00:05:39.399 --> 00:05:47.359
And when I click on bookmark, this dialog box comes down and it gives me this bookmark

00:05:47.359 --> 00:05:48.359
application link.

00:05:48.359 --> 00:05:54.000
So I can copy this and I'll paste it into a browser.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.760
And the application is restored with the same state that we had over here.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:01.959
They both say hello world.

00:06:01.959 --> 00:06:08.640
And so for implementing bookmarking for simple applications, that's really all you need to do.

00:06:14.640 --> 00:06:22.720
Okay, oh yes, and I'll show you how this works in an application that's deployed in our gallery.

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:23.720
This is an example application.

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:29.600
Again, this is also very simple, but I want to show you what the URL looks like.

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:33.040
So there's just a slider here that controls the number of observations.

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:38.480
So I'll just move it up to, let's say, there's 241.

00:06:38.480 --> 00:06:41.799
So and then I hit bookmark.

00:06:41.799 --> 00:06:44.239
This is what comes down.

00:06:44.239 --> 00:06:46.160
This is this URL.

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:52.320
And I paste it into a new browser window.

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:54.320
I get the same result here.

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:55.320
Okay.

00:06:55.320 --> 00:07:06.640
All right, so this is an example of a URL encoded bookmark.

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:11.200
And what that means is that, what that looks like is, first you have your, you know, this

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:12.839
is your path to your application here.

00:07:12.839 --> 00:07:18.119
And then after that, there's this question mark and a bunch of stuff after it.

00:07:18.119 --> 00:07:24.239
So what this is saying is, yeah, I won't go into the, you know, you don't have to generally

00:07:24.239 --> 00:07:29.119
know the details, but I'll explain this to you briefly, is this means these are the inputs

00:07:29.119 --> 00:07:33.600
and then there's an input named N with the value 1, 2, 3, and input named text with the

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:34.600
value ABC.

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:39.760
Okay, so that's what that would be for this particular example.

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:42.760
But that's not the only way that we can do bookmarking.

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:49.920
So another way to do it is to use bookmarks that are saved on the server.

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:56.600
So for these type of bookmarks, instead of encoding all this information about these

00:07:56.600 --> 00:08:05.480
inputs in the URL, all of that is saved on disk and then it's given an ID.

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:13.040
And so, when you want to send a URL to somebody with that state, the URL is, just includes

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:18.799
this part that says state ID equals and then, you know, whatever that unique ID is.

00:08:18.799 --> 00:08:26.220
Okay, so, oops, all right, so I'll talk about some of the, in depth about some of the differences

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:30.640
between these two types of bookmarking in just a bit.

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:36.200
First I'm going to show you how to save to server bookmarkings or how you use it.

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:40.780
So it's very similar to the URL-encoded bookmarking.

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:45.520
So the UI just takes, you know, this function, add a bookmark button, the only real difference

00:08:45.520 --> 00:08:55.000
is you need to have this argument enable bookmarking, set it to server instead of URL.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.960
And that's it, that's the only difference.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:01.880
You know, from the perspective of somebody who's writing the code.

00:09:01.880 --> 00:09:09.280
All right, so here's some of the differences between these two types of bookmarking.

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:13.400
For the URL-encoded bookmarks, there's, as we said, there's no state saved on the server,

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:18.440
all of the state is contained in the URL and if it's saved to server, it's obviously the

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:22.359
state is served on the server.

00:09:22.359 --> 00:09:27.559
For URL-encoded bookmarks, the URLs can become long.

00:09:27.559 --> 00:09:31.500
So if you have a lot of, you know, like those examples that I showed you just have one input

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:38.359
or two inputs, but if you have a lot of inputs for your application, those, or, you know,

00:09:38.359 --> 00:09:44.599
if those inputs have very large values, like, you know, if you've got a text input with

00:09:44.599 --> 00:09:49.400
a very long string that somebody's typed in, the URL can become very long and that can

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:51.880
be a little unwieldy if you're sending it to somebody.

00:09:51.880 --> 00:09:57.520
And if it's saved to server, it's always a short URL, the state ID is always the same

00:09:57.520 --> 00:10:00.919
size.

00:10:00.919 --> 00:10:06.520
And because the URLs are long with URL-encoded bookmarks, you can run into problems with

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:07.979
some browsers.

00:10:07.979 --> 00:10:13.760
Some browsers can only have, take URLs that are up to about 2,000 characters in length

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:19.039
and if your URL exceeds that, I believe it'll just get truncated and so when you try to

00:10:19.039 --> 00:10:22.599
restore your application, it probably won't restore correctly.

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:30.679
And if the state is saved on the server, there's no limit to how much data you can store.

00:10:30.679 --> 00:10:36.400
For URL-encoded bookmarks, you can't save files that have been uploaded in that URL,

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:40.719
but if it's saved to the server, you can.

00:10:40.719 --> 00:10:45.840
And finally, these URL-encoded bookmarks, as of now, they can, well, these can work

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:47.599
on any hosting platform.

00:10:47.599 --> 00:10:54.440
So like ShinyServer or ShinyApps.io or RStudio Connect, whereas the saved server bookmarks

00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:58.640
work on ShinyServer only right now.

00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:03.799
Okay, so I'll go into that for a little bit more depth here.

00:11:03.799 --> 00:11:10.919
When we talk about deploying the bookmarkable apps, the various hosting platforms, here's

00:11:10.919 --> 00:11:14.320
a table for what you can do on the various hosting platforms.

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:20.239
So when you're just running these applications locally on your own machine, like I'm doing

00:11:20.239 --> 00:11:28.039
right now in these examples or when you're developing an application, both types of bookmarking

00:11:28.039 --> 00:11:29.039
will work.

00:11:29.039 --> 00:11:35.520
If you have ShinyServer Pro, you can use both types of bookmarking and same is true for

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:38.719
ShinyServer Open Source.

00:11:38.719 --> 00:11:44.320
If you're deploying your app to ShinyApps.io, you can use the URL-encoded bookmarks, but

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:48.919
the saved server ones are still in development.

00:11:48.919 --> 00:11:53.119
And the same is true for if you're using RStudio Connect.

00:11:53.119 --> 00:11:57.039
The URL-encoded bookmarks will just work, but the saved server bookmarks, there's still

00:11:57.039 --> 00:12:02.200
some work that needs to be done for that to function.

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:11.880
Okay, so those are some very simple apps, applications, and for a certain class of applications,

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:17.679
it is that easy to turn on bookmarking, you know, just to add a few lines of code.

00:12:17.679 --> 00:12:25.359
But for more sophisticated applications that have more complex behavior, there might be

00:12:25.359 --> 00:12:27.359
some other things that you need to do.

00:12:27.359 --> 00:12:34.760
So that's what I'm calling advanced bookmarking.

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:42.880
So now we're going to get into some technical details about these applications.

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:51.479
So the simple application that I showed you before is what I'm calling a fully input-dependent

00:12:51.479 --> 00:12:54.719
application.

00:12:54.719 --> 00:12:59.479
This term is just something I made up, but there may be a better name for it, but I couldn't

00:12:59.479 --> 00:13:01.520
think of one offhand.

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:05.400
So if you've got suggestions, let me know.

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:12.239
Alright, so for this type of application, the state of the outputs at time T is fully

00:13:12.239 --> 00:13:16.359
determined by the state of the inputs at time T.

00:13:16.359 --> 00:13:20.239
So that means that, you know, whatever the value of the input was before, if I had typed

00:13:20.239 --> 00:13:28.320
in something besides hello world before, and then I change it to say hello world, whatever

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:34.799
the previous value was, that does not impact the current state of that text output.

00:13:34.799 --> 00:13:43.500
Alright, for these types of applications, bookmarking should just work.

00:13:43.500 --> 00:13:45.080
And here's some diagrams.

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:51.919
If you've read the article that we have in our Shiny Dev Center about reactivity, these

00:13:51.919 --> 00:14:00.000
diagrams may look familiar, but this is a very simple relationship between an input

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:01.000
and an output.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.880
So we've got input $n and output $text.

00:14:04.880 --> 00:14:10.179
So it's just render text takes input n and that's the value of output $text.

00:14:10.179 --> 00:14:15.739
So whenever input $n changes, output $text changes.

00:14:15.739 --> 00:14:21.500
And the value of this doesn't depend, it depends only on the current state of input $n.

00:14:21.500 --> 00:14:23.440
And you may even have a chain of these things.

00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:32.539
So here is input $n is being used by this reactive called n1, and then output $text

00:14:32.539 --> 00:14:38.900
uses n1 to get the content that it's going to display.

00:14:38.900 --> 00:14:44.219
So this is sort of a chain with this reactive value, input $n, reactive expression, and

00:14:44.219 --> 00:14:47.219
then this output.

00:14:47.219 --> 00:14:53.659
But again, this has a similar relationship where output $text depends only on the current

00:14:53.659 --> 00:14:58.099
state of this input, and it could depend on the state of multiple inputs as long as it's

00:14:58.099 --> 00:15:02.179
just the current state of them and not any previous states.

00:15:03.179 --> 00:15:09.179
Okay, now contrast that with what I'm calling a partly input-dependent application.

00:15:09.179 --> 00:15:16.580
Again, if you've got suggestions for better terminology, I'd be happy to hear that.

00:15:16.580 --> 00:15:20.820
So the state of the outputs at time t is only partly determined by the state of the inputs

00:15:20.820 --> 00:15:22.380
at time t.

00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:27.979
So other things may influence it, including inputs at previous times or perhaps, you know,

00:15:27.979 --> 00:15:29.179
external data sources.

00:15:32.179 --> 00:15:37.179
And for these applications, they'll require a bit more code for bookmarking to work.

00:15:37.179 --> 00:15:40.619
All right, here's an example.

