00:19:03.780 --> 00:19:11.780
Okay, so in order to deal with this sort of problem, there's some callbacks that, there's

00:19:12.380 --> 00:19:17.380
some functions that you can use to register callbacks when an application is bookmarked

00:19:17.380 --> 00:19:19.380
and when it's restored.

00:19:19.380 --> 00:19:23.380
So, because in, for this particular application, we need to save some extra state.

00:19:23.380 --> 00:19:26.380
That's not just the current input values.

00:19:26.380 --> 00:19:29.380
The current input values are saved automatically when you bookmark.

00:19:29.380 --> 00:19:33.380
But this, we need to save some other information as well.

00:19:33.979 --> 00:19:41.979
So, these two callback registration functions are onBookmark and onRestore.

00:19:41.979 --> 00:19:49.979
So, what this one does is, we call onBookmark and we pass it a function that takes one argument

00:19:49.979 --> 00:20:00.979
state, and what it does is, when it executes this, when the user clicks the bookmark button,

00:20:01.579 --> 00:20:05.579
so, and it saves val$sum into these state values.

00:20:05.579 --> 00:20:11.579
So, this state$values is a, it's essentially a list, and you can just put in arbitrary

00:20:11.579 --> 00:20:13.579
information in there.

00:20:13.579 --> 00:20:18.579
So, state$values, $currentsum, we're just saving the current sum in there.

00:20:18.579 --> 00:20:26.579
And, when we restore the application, instead of starting up here where the sum is 0,

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:33.180
with starting with that value, what we end up doing is, we extract the saved current

00:20:33.180 --> 00:20:37.180
sum out of the state and put that in val$sum.

00:20:37.180 --> 00:20:45.180
Okay, and this is, well, this is part of the, this will get us partway there.

00:20:45.180 --> 00:20:48.180
Now, let me show you what happens if we run this.

00:20:48.780 --> 00:20:50.780
Okay.

00:20:53.780 --> 00:20:55.780
Okay, this is the application list.

00:20:55.780 --> 00:20:59.780
It's the same code, except there's these bookmark and restore callbacks.

00:21:02.780 --> 00:21:12.780
Okay, so, let's say I click add a bunch of times, bookmark it, and if you can see this,

00:21:13.380 --> 00:21:17.380
there's this extra part of the URL called values, and $currentsum is 200.

00:21:17.380 --> 00:21:23.380
So, that's the value that I saved in there with that on bookmark callback function.

00:21:23.380 --> 00:21:27.380
If I paste that into my browser, here's what I get.

00:21:29.380 --> 00:21:31.380
It looks a little different.

00:21:31.380 --> 00:21:36.380
So, here the sum is 200, and here the sum is 250.

00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:40.380
So, that's possibly a little bit better, but that's not quite right.

00:21:40.979 --> 00:21:43.979
And let's see why that is.

00:21:49.979 --> 00:21:55.979
Okay, well, what's happening is that there's the, after the application is restored,

00:21:55.979 --> 00:22:00.979
input $add has some value, like 4.

00:22:00.979 --> 00:22:03.979
That's the number of, actually, that's the number of times, it's an action button,

00:22:03.979 --> 00:22:06.979
and that's the number of times the action button has been clicked.

00:22:07.579 --> 00:22:10.579
And because it has a value of 4, it triggers this observer.

00:22:12.579 --> 00:22:14.579
It triggers this observer.

00:22:14.579 --> 00:22:20.579
So, the sum before this observer fired was 200,

00:22:20.579 --> 00:22:25.579
and then, that's right after the application was restored,

00:22:25.579 --> 00:22:30.579
and then this observer gets triggered, and then the sum goes up to 250,

00:22:30.579 --> 00:22:34.579
because it thinks that we clicked the add button one extra time.

00:22:35.180 --> 00:22:38.180
So, and this is because of the way that action buttons work.

00:22:38.180 --> 00:22:43.180
They have some numeric value that represents the number of times they're clicked,

00:22:43.180 --> 00:22:49.180
and for this observer event, if that number, if that value is above 0,

00:22:49.180 --> 00:22:52.180
then it will execute this expression here.

00:22:53.180 --> 00:22:56.180
So, one way out of this, it's not the only way out of this,

00:22:56.180 --> 00:22:59.180
but one way out of this is to not bookmark the add button.

00:22:59.780 --> 00:23:03.780
So that when the app is restored, it will start with a value of 0

00:23:03.780 --> 00:23:07.780
and won't fire this observer event.

00:23:09.780 --> 00:23:13.780
So, and this is what we just saw.

00:23:14.780 --> 00:23:19.780
In order to exclude a value from being bookmarked,

00:23:19.780 --> 00:23:22.780
there's a function called setBookmarkExclude.

00:23:23.780 --> 00:23:26.780
So, we're just saying setBookmarkExclude,

00:23:27.380 --> 00:23:30.380
and the name of the thing that we want to exclude is add.

00:23:30.380 --> 00:23:33.380
And this can be, you know, you can pass in a vector of names.

00:23:33.380 --> 00:23:35.380
We're just excluding one value here.

00:23:36.380 --> 00:23:38.380
So, let's try running this.

00:23:39.380 --> 00:23:41.380
Okay, close that.

00:23:43.380 --> 00:23:45.380
Run this.

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:49.380
Okay, so,

00:23:50.380 --> 00:23:53.380
sum of 200, hit bookmark.

00:23:53.979 --> 00:23:55.979
Copy this.

00:23:56.979 --> 00:23:59.979
And in the new browser tab,

00:23:59.979 --> 00:24:01.979
the sum now displays 200.

00:24:02.979 --> 00:24:04.979
And if you were watching very closely,

00:24:04.979 --> 00:24:08.979
this is the current URL that I have.

00:24:08.979 --> 00:24:10.979
Inputs n equals 50,

00:24:10.979 --> 00:24:13.979
and then there's this values current sum equals 200.

00:24:14.979 --> 00:24:16.979
And in my previous attempt,

00:24:16.979 --> 00:24:19.979
there's also this add equals 4

00:24:19.979 --> 00:24:22.979
that was being saved in the state there.

00:24:23.579 --> 00:24:25.579
In my current attempt, that's no longer there,

00:24:25.579 --> 00:24:27.579
and that's because we excluded them.

00:24:27.579 --> 00:24:29.579
So, that worked.

00:24:29.579 --> 00:24:31.579
Great.

00:24:34.579 --> 00:24:36.579
Alright, and this is again what we saw.

00:24:36.579 --> 00:24:38.579
We started with this

00:24:39.579 --> 00:24:41.579
state of the application

00:24:41.579 --> 00:24:43.579
where the sum was 200, we bookmarked it,

00:24:43.579 --> 00:24:45.579
and then when we restored it,

00:24:45.579 --> 00:24:47.579
it restored the correct value of 200.

00:24:49.579 --> 00:24:51.579
Okay, so,

00:24:52.180 --> 00:24:54.180
so for these sorts of applications,

00:24:56.180 --> 00:24:58.180
where the state of the application

00:24:58.180 --> 00:25:00.180
is a little bit more complex

00:25:00.180 --> 00:25:02.180
than those fully input-dependent ones

00:25:02.180 --> 00:25:04.180
that I described in the beginning,

00:25:05.180 --> 00:25:07.180
there are these useful callback functions.

00:25:07.180 --> 00:25:09.180
So, there's onbookmark

00:25:09.180 --> 00:25:11.180
and onbookmarked.

00:25:11.180 --> 00:25:13.180
This function,

00:25:13.180 --> 00:25:15.180
so the way that these pairs of functions work

00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:17.180
are

00:25:17.180 --> 00:25:19.180
when somebody clicks a bookmark button,

00:25:19.780 --> 00:25:21.780
just before Shiny actually

00:25:21.780 --> 00:25:23.780
saves the state of the application,

00:25:23.780 --> 00:25:25.780
it runs this onbookmark callback,

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:27.780
and then afterwards, it runs this onbookmarked callback.

00:25:27.780 --> 00:25:29.780
So, there's some reason

00:25:29.780 --> 00:25:31.780
that you'd want to use these two different functions.

00:25:31.780 --> 00:25:33.780
And for restoring,

00:25:33.780 --> 00:25:35.780
there's a similar pair.

00:25:35.780 --> 00:25:37.780
There's onrestore,

00:25:37.780 --> 00:25:39.780
which happens just before the application is restored,

00:25:39.780 --> 00:25:41.780
and then onrestored,

00:25:41.780 --> 00:25:43.780
and that gets called

00:25:43.780 --> 00:25:45.780
just after the application is restored.

00:25:46.380 --> 00:25:48.380
And in the documentation,

00:25:48.380 --> 00:25:50.380
there's some examples

00:25:50.380 --> 00:25:52.380
that explain when you'd want to use

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:54.380
these two different things.

00:25:54.380 --> 00:25:56.380
And finally, if you want to exclude values

00:25:56.380 --> 00:25:58.380
from bookmarking,

00:25:58.380 --> 00:26:00.380
there's the setbookmarkexclude function.

00:26:00.380 --> 00:26:02.380
So, I excluded the action button,

00:26:02.380 --> 00:26:04.380
that add action button,

00:26:04.380 --> 00:26:06.380
but there's, you know,

00:26:06.380 --> 00:26:08.380
there may be other types of things

00:26:08.380 --> 00:26:10.380
that you'd like to exclude.

00:26:10.380 --> 00:26:12.380
Okay, so, you know,

00:26:12.380 --> 00:26:14.380
going back to our original story here,

00:26:14.979 --> 00:26:16.979
and you've set it to a particular state.

00:26:16.979 --> 00:26:18.979
So, now that you've learned

00:26:18.979 --> 00:26:20.979
something about bookmarking,

00:26:20.979 --> 00:26:22.979
you probably could write

00:26:22.979 --> 00:26:24.979
an email like this.

00:26:24.979 --> 00:26:26.979
Here's the latest data,

00:26:26.979 --> 00:26:28.979
and just send a URL,

00:26:28.979 --> 00:26:30.979
and that will send

00:26:30.979 --> 00:26:32.979
not just the application,

00:26:32.979 --> 00:26:34.979
but the work that you've done

00:26:34.979 --> 00:26:36.979
in the application.

00:26:36.979 --> 00:26:38.979
And if you'd like

00:26:38.979 --> 00:26:40.979
to learn more about it,

00:26:40.979 --> 00:26:42.979
you can visit the Shiny Dev Center.

00:26:43.579 --> 00:26:45.579
We have an article section,

00:26:45.579 --> 00:26:47.579
the articles page,

00:26:47.579 --> 00:26:49.579
and then there's a section in there

00:26:49.579 --> 00:26:51.579
called bookmarking state.

00:26:51.579 --> 00:26:53.579
And that includes some more technical details

00:26:53.579 --> 00:26:55.579
if you'd like to learn more about it.

00:26:55.579 --> 00:26:57.579
So, there it is.

