00:29:14.579 --> 00:29:16.579
Okay. In the

00:29:16.579 --> 00:29:18.579
save to server mode, is the user able to download

00:29:18.579 --> 00:29:20.579
the file that contains the saved state

00:29:20.579 --> 00:29:22.579
of the application

00:29:22.579 --> 00:29:24.579
in addition to getting the app URL?

00:29:26.579 --> 00:29:28.579
I believe this is

00:29:28.579 --> 00:29:30.579
technically possible

00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:33.180
because

00:29:33.180 --> 00:29:35.180
the state does include

00:29:35.180 --> 00:29:37.180
the directory

00:29:37.180 --> 00:29:39.180
where all these files are stored.

00:29:39.180 --> 00:29:41.180
Whenever a state is saved

00:29:41.180 --> 00:29:43.180
to the server

00:29:43.180 --> 00:29:45.180
a new directory is

00:29:45.180 --> 00:29:47.180
created and all the necessary

00:29:47.180 --> 00:29:49.180
information is saved in there and it should be possible

00:29:49.180 --> 00:29:51.180
to retrieve that.

00:29:51.180 --> 00:29:53.180
There's not

00:29:53.180 --> 00:29:55.180
a simple API

00:29:55.180 --> 00:29:57.180
exposed to do that.

00:29:57.180 --> 00:29:59.180
It is possible to find that directory

00:29:59.780 --> 00:30:01.780
you can zip up all the files in that directory

00:30:01.780 --> 00:30:03.780
if you wanted.

00:30:03.780 --> 00:30:05.780
Yes, it's possible, but

00:30:05.780 --> 00:30:07.780
it's not

00:30:07.780 --> 00:30:09.780
trivial for most users

00:30:09.780 --> 00:30:11.780
I think.

00:30:13.780 --> 00:30:15.780
Are there performance implications for using bookmarkable state?

00:30:17.780 --> 00:30:19.780
For bookmarking, there's no

00:30:19.780 --> 00:30:21.780
if you just turn it on for your

00:30:21.780 --> 00:30:23.780
application, there is no overhead

00:30:25.780 --> 00:30:27.780
performance penalty.

00:30:28.380 --> 00:30:30.380
It's only when the bookmarking actually occurs

00:30:30.380 --> 00:30:32.380
that there's any

00:30:32.380 --> 00:30:34.380
computation.

00:30:34.380 --> 00:30:36.380
In many cases, if you're just saving

00:30:36.380 --> 00:30:38.380
the values of inputs, it's a very small

00:30:38.380 --> 00:30:40.380
amount of data so it happens very quickly.

00:30:40.380 --> 00:30:42.380
The one place

00:30:42.380 --> 00:30:44.380
it can get large is

00:30:44.380 --> 00:30:46.380
if you have large uploaded files.

00:30:46.380 --> 00:30:48.380
If you save the state

00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:50.380
it will make a copy of these

00:30:50.380 --> 00:30:52.380
uploaded files.

00:30:54.380 --> 00:30:56.380
That could potentially

00:30:56.979 --> 00:30:58.979
consume a lot of disk space on the server.

00:31:02.979 --> 00:31:04.979
Is there security value of using

00:31:04.979 --> 00:31:06.979
the server versus URL method?

00:31:10.979 --> 00:31:12.979
With the URL encoded bookmarks

00:31:14.979 --> 00:31:16.979
all of the state is

00:31:16.979 --> 00:31:18.979
at least the state for all the inputs

00:31:18.979 --> 00:31:20.979
is encoded right there in the URL.

00:31:20.979 --> 00:31:22.979
If somebody else is able to

00:31:22.979 --> 00:31:24.979
get a hold of that URL

00:31:25.579 --> 00:31:27.579
they can see

00:31:27.579 --> 00:31:29.579
what inputs

00:31:29.579 --> 00:31:31.579
one has set.

00:31:33.579 --> 00:31:35.579
Depending on your

00:31:35.579 --> 00:31:37.579
situation, it may or may not be

00:31:37.579 --> 00:31:39.579
a security issue.

00:31:39.579 --> 00:31:41.579
If the app also requires a login

00:31:41.579 --> 00:31:43.579
to Shiny Server Pro

00:31:43.579 --> 00:31:45.579
or RStudio Connect

00:31:45.579 --> 00:31:47.579
then

00:31:47.579 --> 00:31:49.579
that's an independent

00:31:49.579 --> 00:31:51.579
thing. If the person

00:31:51.579 --> 00:31:53.579
is not able to access the application

00:31:54.180 --> 00:31:56.180
then it's possible that

00:31:56.180 --> 00:31:58.180
information in the URL

00:31:58.180 --> 00:32:00.180
is not

00:32:00.180 --> 00:32:02.180
going to be all that useful for them.

00:32:02.180 --> 00:32:04.180
For server

00:32:04.180 --> 00:32:06.180
side bookmarking

00:32:10.180 --> 00:32:12.180
I don't think

00:32:12.180 --> 00:32:14.180
there should be any security issues other than

00:32:14.180 --> 00:32:16.180
the state obviously is saved on the server

00:32:16.180 --> 00:32:18.180
so if somebody

00:32:18.180 --> 00:32:20.180
has access

00:32:20.180 --> 00:32:22.180
to the server

00:32:22.780 --> 00:32:24.780
they might need super user access

00:32:24.780 --> 00:32:26.780
then they can look at different state files

00:32:26.780 --> 00:32:28.780
but if they have

00:32:28.780 --> 00:32:30.780
super user access to the server you have

00:32:30.780 --> 00:32:32.780
security issues anyway.

00:32:34.780 --> 00:32:36.780
If you have dynamic UI elements

00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:38.780
i.e. one UI element

00:32:38.780 --> 00:32:40.780
reacting to another, is there any

00:32:40.780 --> 00:32:42.780
issue with the order in which the UI elements are

00:32:42.780 --> 00:32:44.780
restored or are they all restored at the same time?

00:32:48.780 --> 00:32:50.780
Restoring dynamic UI

00:32:51.380 --> 00:32:53.380
was actually one of the challenging bits

00:32:53.380 --> 00:32:55.380
in implementing bookmarking

00:32:55.380 --> 00:32:57.380
for Shiny to make sure that that behaves

00:32:57.380 --> 00:32:59.380
seamlessly.

00:33:03.380 --> 00:33:05.380
Typically

00:33:05.380 --> 00:33:07.380
it depends on

00:33:07.380 --> 00:33:09.380
the specifics of your

00:33:09.380 --> 00:33:11.380
application.

00:33:11.380 --> 00:33:13.380
We try to make it so that

00:33:13.380 --> 00:33:15.380
for

00:33:15.380 --> 00:33:17.380
if your application has any dynamic UI

00:33:17.380 --> 00:33:19.380
