a similar question.

00:36:19.580 --> 00:36:21.580
Asking a similar question.

00:36:21.580 --> 00:36:23.580
The

00:36:23.580 --> 00:36:25.580
answer is you'd have to use it

00:36:25.580 --> 00:36:27.580
the best way right now is to use

00:36:27.580 --> 00:36:29.580
standard Unix

00:36:29.580 --> 00:36:31.580
administration tools.

00:36:31.580 --> 00:36:33.580
I see

00:36:33.580 --> 00:36:35.580
one more here.

00:36:36.179 --> 00:36:38.179
When bookmarking

00:36:38.179 --> 00:36:40.179
using state IDs

00:36:40.179 --> 00:36:42.179
can you examine

00:36:42.179 --> 00:36:44.179
input parameter values

00:36:44.179 --> 00:36:46.179
server side in some way?

00:36:51.179 --> 00:36:53.179
If this question is asking

00:36:53.179 --> 00:36:55.179
what I think it's asking

00:36:55.179 --> 00:36:57.179
I think

00:36:57.179 --> 00:36:59.179
when the

00:36:59.179 --> 00:37:01.179
onbookmark

00:37:01.179 --> 00:37:03.179
callback

00:37:03.179 --> 00:37:05.179
is invoked

00:37:05.780 --> 00:37:07.780
or when the onstore

00:37:07.780 --> 00:37:09.780
callback is invoked

00:37:09.780 --> 00:37:11.780
you can look at the state

00:37:11.780 --> 00:37:13.780
and

00:37:13.780 --> 00:37:15.780
if this question is asking

00:37:15.780 --> 00:37:17.780
about examining those values

00:37:17.780 --> 00:37:19.780
offline

00:37:19.780 --> 00:37:21.780
outside of a session

00:37:21.780 --> 00:37:23.780
the answer is yes it is possible

00:37:23.780 --> 00:37:25.780
when the files are saved on the server

00:37:29.780 --> 00:37:31.780
that state object

00:37:31.780 --> 00:37:33.780
is saved as an RDS object

00:37:34.379 --> 00:37:36.379
which R can just read in

00:37:36.379 --> 00:37:38.379
read RDS and then you can examine

00:37:38.379 --> 00:37:40.379
the contents of it.

00:37:40.379 --> 00:37:42.379
It is possible to look at the contents

00:37:42.379 --> 00:37:44.379
of those input values.

